o manually publish — this doesn't trigger a build for a static site (or uses minimal minutes)\n\nBut wait — the simplest is to use `netlify deploy --prod` which deploys without a build, just uploads files. This is what the user wants.\n\nBut first, do they have the netlify CLI? Let me check. And is the repo cloned locally?\n\nLet me also be careful: \"without triggering netlify credits consumption\" — the user might mean they have a limited Netlify plan and don't want to burn build minutes. Direct deploys typically don't consume build minutes the same way git-triggered builds do.\n\nLet me first check:\n1. Is there a local clone of the repo?\n2. Is the netlify CLI installed?\n3. What's the Netlify site connected to the GitHub repo (if any)?\n\nLet me do these checks in parallel.\n\nWait — I should also think about: the user said \"push it all into the repo nicely for me\". So they want me to:\n- Get the patched HTML into the repo\n- Commit it nicely\n- Push\n\nAnd separately: \"do ensure it does show on my https://akcloud.netlify.app/\" — they want the live site updated\n\"without triggering netlify credits consumption\" — they want to avoid using build minutes\n\nThe trick is: if the GitHub repo is connected to Netlify, then a git push will trigger a Netlify build (consuming minutes). So I need to:\n- Either: push to GitHub AND also do a direct deploy to override\n- Or: skip the git push and just do a direct deploy to Netlify\n- Or: push to a branch that's not auto-deployed, then manual promote\n\nHmm. Let me check the state of things first.\n\nActually, you know what — the simplest thing: \n1. First check if the repo is even cloned locally\n2. Check git status\n3. Check netlify CLI\n\nIf the repo is at `C:\\Users\\LLM-Test\\Downloads\\akcloud-site` or similar, I can just copy the file in and push. Then for the deploy, I can use `netlify deploy --prod` with the specific file.\n\nLet me start exploring.",
