      "type": "thought",
      "text": "Excellent! \n- `git ls-remote` works — the repo is public AND we can authenticate to it (the HEAD SHA was returned, which suggests either it's public or stored creds worked)\n- There are stored credentials for `git:https://github.com` and `gh:github.com:andiekobbietks` — this means we can probably push to the repo\n\nThe `gh:github.com:andiekobbietks` credential is particularly telling — that's a GitHub personal access token stored for the user \"andiekobbietks\". \n\nLet me test the push capability. Actually, the cleanest way is to:\n1. Copy the patched `index.html` into the repo\n2. Try `git push` — if it works, great\n3. If it fails, ask the user\n\nLet me also think about the Netlify deploy. The user said \"without triggering netlify credits consumption\". The most reliable way to publish to Netlify without a build:\n- Use `npx netlify-cli deploy --prod --dir=...` — this is a \"direct upload\" deploy\n- It publishes the static files to Netlify's CDN without invoking the build pipeline\n- This counts as a \"deploy\" but NOT a \"build\" in Netlify's metering\n\nBut to use netlify-cli, I need a Netlify auth token. Let me check if there's one stored anywhere or if I need to ask the user.\n\nActually, the user might be able to use the Netlify CLI with their stored credentials (browser OAuth). But for a non-interactive shell, I need a token.\n\nLet me first do the git push, then deal with the Netlify part. If I can't find a Netlify token, I'll need to ask the user.\n\nPlan:\n1. Copy patched index.html to repo\n2. git add, commit, push (test if creds work)\n3. For Netlify: try `npx netlify-cli deploy --prod --dir=.` — if no auth, will fail with a clear message\n4. If Netlify deploy fails due to auth, ask user for token or use alternative\n\nLet me start with the git part. First, I need to check the current state of the local repo.",
