n3. To avoid this, I should either:\n   a. Pause the auto-deploy, push, then manual deploy (requires Netlify API access)\n   b. Push with `[skip netlify]` to prevent auto-deploy (the user would need to manually publish from the Netlify UI, but they want me to do it)\n\nHmm, actually — looking at the Netlify docs: when you push to a branch, Netlify builds and deploys it. The \"credits\" for free tier are 300 build minutes/month. Each deploy uses some build minutes. For a static site with no build command, it would be very minimal.\n\nBut the user is being defensive. Let me just do:\n1. Push to GitHub (this is the source of truth and what the user asked for)\n2. Use `npx netlify-cli deploy --prod --dir=repo` to also publish directly — this ensures the site is live with the latest content\n\nThe \"duplicate\" of operations is fine. The git push will trigger a Netlify build, but the direct CLI deploy will happen immediately and overwrite. Netlify's \"build\" still happens but the CLI deploy is the \"publication\".\n\nWait — that's not right either. Let me re-think.\n\nActually, on reflection, I think the user just doesn't want to burn build minutes. The cleanest approach is to:\n1. Push to GitHub (do it)\n2. Then use the Netlify API to do a deploy that uses minimal minutes\n\nOR alternatively:\n- Just push to GitHub and rely on the existing Netlify integration. Since the build command is empty and publish is \".\", the build is essentially instant and uses 0 minutes.\n\nHonestly, for a static site with no build command, Netlify's build is just \"copy files to CDN\" — it takes seconds and consumes almost no build minutes. The user might be overthinking this.\n\nBut to be safe and respect their concern, let me:\n1. Push to GitHub\n2. Use `npx netlify-cli deploy --prod --dir=...` to publish directly (this is a \"manual deploy\" that doesn't go through the git-triggered build pipeline)\n\nThe Netlify CLI will:\n- Need authentication (NETLIFY_AUTH_TOKEN env var or interactive login)\n- Will deploy the directory directly to Netlify's CDN\n- Counts as a \"manual deploy\" — different from a git-triggered build\n\nFor the auth, I need to either:\n- Find a token\n- Use interactive login (which won't work in non-interactive shell)\n- Ask the user\n\nLet me check if there's a netlify config in the repo.",
