      "type": "thought",
      "text": "The `CORNER` variable is used in the inline admin modal (the secure access dialog). It creates the corner marker via a separate `<div>` element. So the admin modals have the green corner marker too.\n\nThe user said \"for each\" — they want this for all the cards. Let me list:\n1. `.card` (Sovereign/Hyperscaler/BYOC) — main feature cards\n2. `.card-outcome` (Early Outcomes cards) — outcomes cards\n3. `.book-modal` — book modal (corner marker, no hover defined)\n4. `.login-modal` — login modal (corner marker, no hover defined)\n5. `.perk-card` — perks cards (uses `.perk-dot`, not a corner marker)\n6. Credits cards (inline-styled, no corner marker)\n7. Admin modal (uses CORNER var)\n\nThe user specifically said \"for each\" — meaning the cards with the green corner marker. So:\n- `.card` ✓\n- `.card-outcome` ✓\n- The book/login modals probably should also get it\n- The admin modal too\n\nBut modals are usually closed (no hover). Let me focus on:\n1. `.card` — main feature cards (the one in the screenshot)\n2. `.card-outcome` — outcomes cards\n\nAnd add the same to modals for consistency when they appear.\n\nAlso, the user mentioned \"as that will make it become a genesis effect almost like providing a magnifier to them\" — this suggests a sense of \"birth\" or \"expansion\" of the green marker, sweeping from the corner to cover the whole card. The magnifier implies it makes the card stand out / come forward.\n\nPlan:\n1. Update `.card::before` and `.card:hover::before` to expand to full border on hover\n2. Update `.card-outcome::before` and `.card-outcome:hover::before` similarly\n3. Update `.book-modal::before` and `.login-modal::before` for consistency (when they appear)\n4. Update the inline `CORNER` variable in the admin JS to include a hover state via the parent card's hover\n\nFor the hover effect, the key insight from the user: \"it should cover the entire space of the element it expand on a bit not just to a point\". So the marker should:\n- Sweep from the 38px corner to cover the entire border\n- Extend slightly beyond the card edge (the \"expand on a bit\" — overshoot/magnifier)\n- Feel alive, not a hard cut\n\nLet me design this:\n\n```css\n.card::before {\n  content: '';\n  position: absolute;\n  top: -1px;\n  left: -1px;\n  width: 38px;\n  height: 38px;\n  border: 2px solid transparent;\n  border-top-color: #39FF14;\n  border-left-color: #39FF14;\n  border-top-left-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 6px #39FF14, 0 0 14px rgba(57,255,20,0.55);\n  transition:\n    width 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1),\n    height 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) 0.06s,\n    border-color 0.35s ease 0.22s,\n    box-shadow 0.45s ease 0.1s,\n    transform 0.45s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) 0.1s;\n  pointer-events: none;\n  z-index: 1;\n}\n.card:hover::before {\n  width: calc(100% + 4px);\n  height: calc(100% + 4px);\n  border-color: #39FF14;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  transform: translate(-2px, -2px); /* counteract the +4px expansion so it stays centered */\n  box-shadow:\n    0 0 10px #39FF14,\n    0 0 28px rgba(57,255,20,0.5),\n    0 0 56px rgba(57,255,20,0.25);\n}\n```\n\nWait, the `transform: translate(-2px, -2px)` would keep the `::before` visually centered around the card. But the `top: -1px; left: -1px` means the `::before` is already offset by -1px from the card's top-left. With `width: calc(100% + 4px)`, the `::before` would extend from -1px to (cardWidth + 3px), which is 4px past the right edge. To center it, we'd need to translate by -2px.\n\nActually, the user wants the marker to \"expand on a bit\" — extend beyond the card. So the `+4px` (extending 2px past each side) is intentional. No need to translate.\n\nLet me drop the translate. The marker will be slightly larger than the card on hover, creating the magnifier effect.\n\nActually, even simpler — let me use a different approach. The default state has the marker at top: -1px, left: -1px (slightly outside the card's border). On hover, expand it to cover the full card including its border area:\n\n```css\n.card::before {\n  content: '';\n  position: absolute;\n  top: -2px;        /* was -1px */\n  left: -2px;       /* was -1px */\n  width: 36px;      /* was 38px */\n  height: 36px;     /* was 38px */\n  border: 2px solid transparent;\n  border-top-color: #39FF14;\n  border-left-color: #39FF14;\n  border-top-left-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 6px #39FF14, 0 0 14px rgba(57,255,20,0.55);\n  transition:\n    width 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1),\n    height 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) 0.06s,\n    border-color 0.35s ease 0.22s,\n    box-shadow 0.45s ease 0.1s;\n  pointer-events: none;\n  z-index: 1;\n}\n.card:hover::before {\n  width: calc(100% + 4px);\n  height: calc(100% + 4px);\n  border-color: #39FF14;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow:\n    0 0 10px #39FF14,\n    0 0 28px rgba(57,255,20,0.5),\n    0 0 56px rgba(57,255,20,0.25);\n}\n```\n\nWait, I'm overcomplicating. Let me keep the original positioning (top: -1px, left: -1px, 38x38) and just expand on hover:\n\n```css\n.card::before {\n  content: '';\n  position: absolute;\n  top: -1px;\n  left: -1px;\n  width: 38px;\n  height: 38px;\n  border: 2px solid transparent;\n  border-top-color: #39FF14;\n  border-left-color: #39FF14;\n  border-top-left-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 6px #39FF14, 0 0 14px rgba(57,255,20,0.55);\n  transition:\n    width 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1),\n    height 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) 0.06s,\n    border-color 0.4s ease 0.22s,\n    box-shadow 0.45s ease 0.1s;\n  pointer-events: none;\n  z-index: 1;\n}\n.card:hover::before {\n  width: calc(100% + 2px);\n  height: calc(100% + 2px);\n  border-color: #39FF14;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow:\n    0 0 10px #39FF14,\n    0 0 28px rgba(57,255,20,0.5),\n    0 0 56px rgba(57,255,20,0.25);\n}\n```\n\nThe `calc(100% + 2px)` means the `::before` extends 1px past the right and bottom edges (since top: -1px, left: -1px is already offset). This creates the \"expand on a bit\" feel.\n\nHmm, but actually I want a more dramatic magnifier effect. Let me bump it to +6px or +8px:\n\n```css\n.card:hover::before {\n  width: calc(100% + 6px);\n  height: calc(100% + 6px);\n  ...\n}\n```\n\nThis would extend 3px past each side, creating a clear \"lift\" effect.\n\nAlso, the `transform` could be used to scale slightly. But the box-shadow also scales, which might be too much. Let me stick with width/height for now.\n\nLet me also think about the timing. The user wants it to feel \"alive\" — not a hard cut. A smooth ease-out with a slight delay between the width and height animations would help. The cubic-bezier I chose (0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) is a strong ease-out that ends slowly, which feels good.\n\nFor the borders, the existing CSS has `border-top` and `border-left` only. I changed to `border: 2px solid transparent` with `border-top-color` and `border-left-color` overrides. This is necessary so the element has border-width defined (otherwise the width/height calculations might be off).\n\nWait, actually, the default border-width is 0 if not specified, and the existing code uses `border-top: 2px solid ...; border-left: 2px solid ...;` which sets the top and left border widths. The bottom and right would be 0. So the element's box-sizing affects the width/height.\n\nTo make the math clean: use `border: 2px solid transparent; border-top-color: #39FF14; border-left-color: #39FF14;` so all 4 sides have width 2px, and on hover I just change the colors.\n\nActually, box-sizing matters here. If the `::before` has `box-sizing: content-box` (default), then `width: 100%` means 100% of the parent's content width, and the borders are added on top. If `box-sizing: border-box`, the width includes the borders.\n\nFor the original 38x38 corner, box-sizing doesn't matter much. For the full-size hover, I need to make sure the `::before` covers the entire card including its border.\n\nLet me set `box-sizing: border-box` to make it predictable.\n\nHmm actually, the simpler approach: keep the original 38x38 sizing, but use `inset: 0` (or equivalent) on hover. But `inset: 0` would override `top: -1px; left: -1px`. Hmm.\n\nLet me think about this differently. The card has:\n- border: 1px solid #242424\n- border-radius: 8px\n- padding: 30px\n\nThe `::before` is positioned at top: -1px, left: -1px with 38x38. This places the `::before` exactly aligned with the card's top-left corner (the `::before` covers the card's border from the outside at the corner).\n\nFor the hover, I want the `::before` to trace the full card outline. The simplest way:\n- `top: -1px; left: -1px;` (same as default)\n- `width: calc(100% + 2px); height: calc(100% + 2px);` (extending 1px past the right and bottom)\n- `border-radius: 8px;` (matching the card's border-radius)\n- All 4 border colors green\n\nThis should work. Let me also add `box-sizing: border-box` to be safe.\n\nActually, with `box-sizing: border-box` and `width: 100%`, the `::before` is 100% of the parent including the parent's padding but NOT the parent's border. The parent (the card) has `border: 1px`. So `width: 100%` would be the card's content+padding width, not including the card's border.\n\nWith `top: -1px; left: -1px`, the `::before` is offset 1px outside the card. So its right edge would be at `left + width = -1 + 100%` = 100% - 1px (from the card's left edge). The card's right edge is at 100% (from the card's left edge, including border). So the `::before` would end 1px BEFORE the card's right edge.\n\nTo make the `::before` end at the card's right edge (1px past, actually), I need `width: calc(100% + 2px)`. Let me verify:\n- `left: -1px`, `width: calc(100% + 2px)` → right edge at `-1 + 100 + 2 = 101%` (1px past the card's right edge)\n- That's the \"expand on a bit\" effect ✓\n\nOK let me write the final CSS.\n\nFor the hover, I also want a slight delay on the border-color change so the green border appears after the expansion has mostly completed. This creates a \"trace then glow\" feel.\n\nLet me also add a transform to the card itself for the \"magnifier\" feel:\n- `transform: translateY(-2px)` on hover\n- This makes the card lift slightly when hovered\n- Combined with the green border expanding, it feels like the card is \"rising\" to meet the user's attention\n\nActually, the user said the marker should \"expand on a bit\" — I think they mean the marker itself should expand a bit. Not the card. So the card shouldn't transform, just the marker.\n\nBut adding a subtle card transform would enhance the magnifier feel. Let me add it.\n\nOK let me write the patch script.\n\nAlso, the user said \"for each\" — I should update:\n1. `.card` (line 48-51)\n2. `.card-outcome` (line 52-55)\n3. Maybe `.book-modal` and `.login-modal` for consistency (line 78, 86)\n4. The admin modal CORNER (line 865) — needs JS changes\n\nFor modals, they don't really have a \"hover\" state since they're not interactive in the same way. But if a user is interacting with a modal form, hovering over the modal could trigger the same effect. Let me add it to all four for consistency.\n\nFor the admin modal CORNER, I can update the inline style to include the transition, but the hover would need to be on the parent card. The current setup uses a separate div for the corner. I can add `transition: ...` to the inline CORNER style and add a hover rule via CSS that targets the card containing the corner.\n\nActually, the admin modals are dynamically created in JS. The CSS for them would need to be in the stylesheet. Let me just add a class to the inline style so I can target it from CSS.\n\nWait, the CORNER is a `<div>` inside the card. The card has `id=\"_d1\"` or `id=\"_d2\"`. I could add a class to the CORNER div, but the CSS would need to know about it.\n\nActually, the simpler approach: don't add the hover effect to modals for now. The user mentioned \"for each\" referring to the cards (the feature cards). Let me focus on `.card` and `.card-outcome` first, and see if they want the modals too.\n\nLet me also think about the `.perk-card` — it has a `.perk-dot` (a small green dot) not a corner marker. The user might want the dot to also expand on hover, but the user said \"that square\" — singular, referring to the corner marker. So I'll leave the perk cards alone.\n\nOK final plan:\n1. Update `.card::before` to use `border: 2px solid transparent; border-top-color: ...; border-left-color: ...;` so all 4 sides have width\n2. Update `.card:hover::before` to expand to `calc(100% + 2px)` width/height with all 4 borders green, increased glow\n3. Add transition with cubic-bezier for smooth feel\n4. Optionally add a slight card lift on hover\n5. Apply same to `.card-outcome`\n\nLet me write the patch.\n\nAlso, the perk-dot could be enhanced — it currently is a small green dot. If the user wants all \"squares\" (markers) to expand, the perk-dot should also expand. But the dot is a circle, not a square. The user said \"that square\" — referring to the L-shaped corner marker. Let me leave the perk-dot for now.\n\nHmm wait, the user said \"when that square is hovered over it should cover the entire space of the element it expand on a bit not just to a point so sort it out for each\" — \"for each\" suggests there are multiple squares. The corner markers are L-shapes (or \"squares\" in the user's terminology). So they want all the corner markers (on cards, modals, etc.) to expand on hover.\n\nOK let me update all of them:\n- `.card` ✓\n- `.card-outcome` ✓\n- `.book-modal` ✓\n- `.login-modal` ✓\n- Admin modal CORNER — needs separate handling\n\nFor the admin modal, the CORNER is an inline style. I can either:\n- Add a class and define CSS rules\n- Or modify the JS to use a different approach\n\nFor modals, they don't have a meaningful \"hover\" state in normal use. But the user said \"for each\", so let me add it to all four card types and the admin modal too.\n\nFor the admin modal, I'll add a class to the CORNER div (e.g., `ak-corner`) and define CSS rules for `.ak-corner` that include the hover effect when the parent card is hovered.\n\nActually, the admin modals are at `_d1` and `_d2` with the corner inside. I can add CSS like:\n```css\n#_d1:hover .ak-corner,\n#_d2:hover .ak-corner {\n  /* hover styles for the corner */\n}\n```\n\nOK let me just do it. Let me write the patch now.\n\nActually, let me also think about whether to add `border-radius: 8px` to the `::before` by default. Currently it has `border-top-left-radius: 8px` only. For the full-size hover, all corners should be rounded. But by default, only the top-left is rounded. I should also add `border-radius: 0` to other corners, or just `border-radius: 8px` to make all corners rounded.\n\nWait, `border-top-left-radius: 8px` makes ONLY the top-left corner rounded. The other corners are square. For the full-size hover, I want all 4 corners rounded. So I'd add `border-radius: 8px` on hover.\n\nOK here's my final CSS:\n\n```css\n.card::before {\n  content: '';\n  position: absolute;\n  top: -1px;\n  left: -1px;\n  width: 38px;\n  height: 38px;\n  border: 2px solid transparent;\n  border-top-color: #39FF14;\n  border-left-color: #39FF14;\n  border-top-left-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow: 0 0 6px #39FF14, 0 0 14px rgba(57,255,20,0.55);\n  pointer-events: none;\n  z-index: 1;\n  transition:\n    width 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1),\n    height 0.5s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1) 0.06s,\n    border-color 0.4s ease 0.22s,\n    box-shadow 0.45s ease 0.1s,\n    border-radius 0.45s ease 0.15s;\n}\n.card:hover::before {\n  width: calc(100% + 2px);\n  height: calc(100% + 2px);\n  border-color: #39FF14;\n  border-radius: 8px;\n  box-shadow:\n    0 0 10px #39FF14,\n    0 0 28px rgba(57,255,20,0.5),\n    0 0 56px rgba(57,255,20,0.25);\n}\n```\n\nThis:\n- Starts as 38x38 L-shape in top-left corner with top+left green borders\n- On hover, expands to cover the entire card (width 100%+2px, height 100%+2px) with all 4 green borders\n- Border-radius animates from corner-only to all-corners\n- Box-shadow glows brighter on hover\n- Smooth easing with subtle delays for a \"trace then glow\" feel\n- Extends 1px past the right and bottom edges of the card (the \"expand on a bit\" magnifier feel)\n\nFor the card itself, I'll add a subtle transform on hover for the \"lift\" feel:\n```css\n.card {\n  ...\n  transition: border-color 0.2s, box-shadow 0.2s, transform 0.4s cubic-bezier(0.22, 1, 0.36, 1);\n}\n.card:hover {\n  ...\n  transform: translateY(-2px);\n}\n```\n\nOK let me write the patch. I'll create a script that:\n1. Updates the `.card` rules\n2. Updates the `.card-outcome` rules\n3. Updates the `.book-modal` and `.login-modal` rules\n4. Updates the admin modal CORNER (adds a class and CSS rules)\n\nLet me write the patch script.",
