      "text": "Interesting! The Odoo website routing:\n- `/appointment/1` → 404\n- `/book-appointment/1` → 404\n- `/odoo/appointment/1` → 200 (this is the actual URL, but it's the Odoo backend, not the public booking page)\n\nWait, `/odoo/appointment/1` returning 200 might just be the Odoo backend redirecting to login. Let me check the actual response body to see if it's a booking page or a login page.\n\nActually, Odoo's public appointment URLs typically don't have `/odoo/` in the path — that's the backend path. The public booking URL might be:\n- `https://andiekobbie.odoo.com/<appointment_type_name>` or similar\n\nLet me do a GET to see what the 200 response actually contains.\n\nActually, the way Odoo Appointment works:\n- When published, the appointment type gets a public URL like `https://andiekobbie.odoo.com/appointment/<id>-<slug>` or similar\n- The exact URL pattern depends on the Odoo version and configuration\n\nLet me also check by GET-ing `/odoo/appointment/1` to see what's there.\n\nActually, let me check the Odoo Appointment documentation. The typical URL for a public appointment page is:\n- `https://<your-odoo-domain>/appointment/<id>`\n\nBut for Odoo Online (Odoo.com hosted), the URLs might be:\n- `https://<your-db>.odoo.com/<appointment_url>` where appointment_url is a custom field\n\nFor the appointment module, the public URL is built from:\n- `appointment_type.website_url` if available\n- Or `f\"/appointment/{appointment_type.id}\"` if website_appointment is installed\n\nLet me query the Odoo API for the actual website_url field.\n\nWait, I can also check the existing appointment.type record to see if there's a website_url or access_token. Let me query more fields.\n\nActually, let me just GET `/odoo/appointment/1` to see what it returns. If it's the booking page, great. If it's a login page, the URL pattern is wrong.\n\nHmm but `/odoo/appointment/1` is the BACKEND path. The PUBLIC path is different. Let me look at the HTML response.\n\nOK let me 